The most likely cause is that you never set the page's `BindingContext` to your ViewModel instance. The bindings have nothing to resolve against.

**Fix — set the BindingContext:**

```csharp
// In your page's code-behind constructor:
public MyPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
}
```

**Also ensure** your ViewModel implements `INotifyPropertyChanged` (or inherits from `ObservableObject` in the MVVM Toolkit) so the UI updates when properties change:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _title;
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; OnPropertyChanged(); }
    }
    // ... same for Description

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler PropertyChanged;
    void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string name = null)
        => PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(name));
}
```

If you prefer less boilerplate, use `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`:

```csharp
public partial class MyViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _title;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _description;
}
```

**TL;DR** — no `BindingContext` = no data shown, even if properties have values.
